Relocation AI Agent
Problem Statement, Strategic Context & Solution Proposal
(Settly AI Agent Platform)
Strategic Context
Settly’s long-term vision is to scale relocation services through a platform-first operational model, where workflows, knowledge, and communication are embedded into the product rather than distributed across internal teams.
However, a structural challenge became clear:
Many of the most time-consuming relocation activities — answering immigration questions, coordinating travel bookings, and supporting document completion — still rely heavily on manual knowledge work performed by operations teams.
This creates three strategic limitations.
Operational scaling limits
Relocation services rely on domain experts (immigration specialists, hosts, operations teams) answering repetitive questions and managing structured processes.
Scaling this model linearly requires hiring more specialists.
Knowledge fragmentation
Critical knowledge is spread across:
internal Slack channels


past cases


immigration experts


government websites and forms


vendor systems


This makes consistent answers difficult and slows down operations.
Platform opportunity for AI augmentation
If Settly can centralize this knowledge and operational reasoning inside the platform, it unlocks:
automated guidance for users


AI-assisted responses for hosts


consistent policy interpretation


reduced reliance on individual experts


This aligns directly with Settly’s broader platform strategy:
transform operational knowledge into scalable platform capabilities.

My Role
As Product Manager driving the AI Agent platform exploration, I focused on translating operational workflows into AI-compatible system architectures.
My responsibilities included:
Identifying high-impact operational workflows where AI could meaningfully reduce manual work


Designing a multi-agent system architecture around relocation workflows


Defining the orchestration layer responsible for routing tasks between agents


Designing the evaluation and benchmarking framework to measure model performance


Working with engineering to prototype the first operational agents


Coordinating domain experts (immigration specialists, hosts) to supply ground-truth datasets


The goal was not simply to build a chatbot.
The objective was to design a scalable AI capability layer based on an orchestrated multi-agent architecture embedded directly into Settly’s operational platform.

Product Context
Relocation management involves many operational workflows that follow structured but knowledge-heavy processes, such as:
Travel coordination
Hosts coordinate flight bookings between:
the user


the vendor


internal teams


While the process is structured, it still involves manual communication steps and message drafting.
Immigration guidance
Immigration cases generate large volumes of repetitive questions, including:
visa timelines


required documents


form completion


eligibility rules


travel restrictions during pending applications


Many answers rely on a combination of official sources (e.g., IND), internal knowledge, and historical case context.
Document and form support
Users frequently request clarification on immigration forms, even though instructions are often embedded within the documents themselves.

Across these workflows we observed consistent characteristics:
high question volume


repetitive tasks


domain-specific knowledge


structured operational workflows


significant risk if answers are incorrect


This made them strong candidates for AI-assisted workflow automation, provided the system could maintain high reliability and traceability.

Problem Identification
1) Knowledge work does not scale linearly
Immigration and relocation expertise currently resides with specific specialists.
When questions arise:
operations teams ask experts in Slack


experts consult government resources


answers are manually written and sent


This process repeats across many similar cases.
Without systematizing this reasoning process, Settly cannot scale expertise efficiently.

2) Critical information exists across many sources
Immigration answers often require combining multiple inputs:
official government websites


immigration law guidance


internal operational knowledge


previous cases


In many situations the correct answer is not explicitly available in a single source, but must be derived through interpretation and domain expertise.
This makes rule-based automation infeasible, and instead requires retrieval-augmented reasoning systems.

3) AI systems must balance correctness and usability
In this domain, errors have different levels of severity.
Minor issues:
tone of response


formatting


wording


Critical issues:
incorrect immigration advice


wrong visa requirements


incorrect legal interpretation


This means evaluation must prioritize factual correctness and policy compliance over stylistic quality.
To address this, we designed a structured evaluation pipeline with domain-expert reference answers (“golden answers”) and automated scoring metrics.

4) Some workflows combine knowledge with system actions
Certain tasks require system interaction, such as checking case status in government portals.
These workflows require:
authenticated systems


multi-step navigation


case-specific data


This means the system must determine when to answer autonomously and when to escalate to human operators, a common design consideration in human-in-the-loop AI systems.

5) Reliable AI requires structured evaluation infrastructure
Unlike traditional product features, AI systems require continuous evaluation and iteration.
During development we observed:
prompt adjustments significantly affect model behavior


evaluation datasets must evolve as new edge cases appear


model performance improves through structured benchmarking


To address this, we implemented an evaluation framework based on curated datasets, golden answers, and automated scoring metrics, enabling systematic model improvement and regression testing.

Activities
To tackle these challenges, I led work across four tracks.

1) Workflow discovery with domain experts
We mapped how immigration specialists and hosts answer real questions.
This involved:
collecting real questions from internal communication channels


identifying the most frequent request types


mapping which sources are consulted to construct answers


This process helped identify where AI agents could augment existing workflows.

2) Multi-Agent Architecture Design
Instead of building a single general-purpose assistant, we designed an orchestrated multi-agent architecture.
Each operational workflow is handled by a specialized agent:
Travel Booking Agent


Immigration Guidance Agent


Document Support Agent


A central agent orchestrator determines which agent should handle a request and provides the necessary context.
This architecture improves:
modularity


domain accuracy


system scalability


It also aligns with modern multi-agent LLM system design patterns.

3) AI Evaluation Framework
To measure performance, we implemented an evaluation system using:
curated datasets of real questions


expert-written “golden answers”


automated evaluation metrics (accuracy, relevance, tone)


This enabled quantitative benchmarking of agent performance and systematic improvement.

4) Gradual Prototyping and Human-in-the-Loop Deployment
Instead of fully automating responses immediately, we introduced AI in assisted workflows:
agents generate draft responses


hosts review and edit


approved responses are sent to users


This approach allowed safe deployment while collecting real-world performance data.

The Solution
The resulting system is an AI Agent Platform built on an orchestrated multi-agent architecture.
The platform combines:
specialized AI agents


retrieval-based knowledge systems


structured workflow logic


evaluation infrastructure



1) Domain-Specific AI Agents
Each workflow is handled by a specialized agent:
Travel Agent
Handles vendor communication and travel booking coordination.
Immigration Agent
Provides immigration guidance using trusted sources and expert knowledge.
Document Agent
Answers questions about forms and documentation.
This specialization reduces ambiguity and improves answer quality.

2) Retrieval-Based Knowledge Layer
Instead of relying on the open internet, the system prioritizes trusted knowledge sources.
Primary sources
official government websites (e.g., IND)


Secondary sources
immigration law firm guidance


internal documentation


This creates a tiered knowledge retrieval system, improving reliability and traceability.

3) Human-in-the-Loop Operation
To maintain operational safety, the system initially operates with human oversight.
AI generates response drafts
Hosts review and approve
Feedback is used to improve the system
This pattern is common in enterprise AI deployments where correctness is critical.

4) Continuous Evaluation Loop
The system includes a structured improvement cycle:
collect real questions


compare AI responses with expert answers


identify failure patterns


refine prompts and system architecture


This ensures measurable improvement over time.

Outcome & Early Signals
Early prototypes demonstrated several promising signals:
agents can draft operational responses with strong contextual awareness


evaluation metrics improve through iterative prompt tuning


domain experts can systematically validate AI outputs


The evaluation framework also provides visibility into:
where agents perform reliably


where additional training data or prompt adjustments are required



Why This Initiative Matters
This project is not simply about adding AI features.
It is about transforming operational knowledge into scalable platform infrastructure.
The AI agent platform enables:
Operational scalability
Expert reasoning can be reused across thousands of relocation cases.
Faster user support
Users receive faster responses without waiting for specialists.
Knowledge centralization
Operational expertise becomes embedded in the platform instead of residing with individuals.
Foundation for intelligent automation
Once workflows and knowledge are structured, the platform can support:
automated case guidance


proactive notifications


workflow orchestration


intelligent document processing



In Summary
By introducing an orchestrated multi-agent architecture with structured evaluation and retrieval systems, Settly can transform operational expertise into scalable product capabilities.
AI agents become a platform layer that augments relocation workflows, enabling the company to scale complex global mobility services without proportional growth in operational headcount.


